The paper deals with the problem of frequent-subgraph mining in evolving graphs, which involves designing algorithms for extracting frequent patterns from a stream of graph updates. This problem is relevant to several areas of computer science, including data structures (cs.DS), social and information networks (cs.SI), databases (cs.DB), machine learning (cs.LG), and software engineering (cs.SE). However, given the focus on graph algorithms and data structures, as well as the use of theoretical analysis and empirical evaluation, we believe that cs.DS and cs.SI are the most likely categories. The other categories are also relevant, but to a lesser extent, as they are more concerned with the applications and implications of the problem rather than the technical details of the algorithms.
